-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
-- OBSERVATIONS
-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

⊢= obs-loop-convergence
  ∴ The ⊢∘ refine loop converged in 2 iterations. Initial translation had
    drift-score 3 (two drifted segments). After one correction pass, drift
    dropped to 1 (acceptable). The loop's convergence was driven by targeted
    segment replacement rather than full retranslation — correct only touched
    2 of 6 sentences, preserving already-good translations.

⊢= obs-drift-taxonomy
  ∴ Two categories of translation drift observed:
    (1) Lexical reordering: "self-bootstrapping metacircular" → "metacircular
    auto-bootstrapping". The Spanish translator reorganized adjective order
    following Spanish syntax norms, which round-tripped into different English.
    (2) Semantic shift: "fills in" → "completa" → "completes". The verb choice
    in Spanish collapsed a nuanced English idiom ("fill in" as template
    population) into a broader verb ("complete"), which back-translated with
    different connotations. Fixed by using "rellenar" (to fill in/populate).

⊢= obs-technical-term-stability
  ∴ Technical terms that were preserved in English form within the Spanish
    text ("metacircular", "LLMs", "Cell", "Scheme", "soft", "hard")
    round-tripped perfectly. Drift occurred exclusively in natural-language
    segments that underwent actual translation. This suggests a heuristic:
    the more technical terms a passage contains, the more stable it is under
    round-trip translation.

⊢= obs-oracle-as-diff
  ∴ The diff cell functions as a semantic diff oracle — it operates at the
    sentence level, comparing meaning rather than tokens. This is inherently
    a soft oracle (requires LLM judgment to assess "does an implementor
    extract the same meaning?"). The oracle cannot crystallize because
    semantic equivalence is undecidable in general. However, the THRESHOLD
    (drift-score ≤ 1 → acceptable) is deterministic — a hard rule wrapping
    a soft evaluation.

⊢= obs-correction-locality
  ∴ The correct cell demonstrates locality of repair: only drifted segments
    are retranslated. This prevents the "cascade problem" where fixing one
    sentence destabilizes others. The ⊨ oracle "corrected preserves
    non-drifted segments" enforces this invariant. In iteration 2, the
    previously-corrected segments round-tripped cleanly, confirming that
    targeted correction does not introduce new drift.

⊢= obs-back-translation-as-verification
  ∴ Back-translation is a verification technique borrowed from professional
    translation practice. In Cell terms, it's a proof-carrying pattern:
    the translation is the "solution" (NP-like), and back-translation + diff
    is the "verifier" (P-like, relatively). The verifier (diff oracle) is
    cheaper than re-doing the full translation because it only compares
    rather than generates. This is structurally identical to Cell's
    solve/substitute pattern from proof-carrying computation.
